What you measure improves

Assessments

believing in people before they believe in themselves

silence the noise around you to listen to the heartbeat within you

It's well worth thinking about ways to reduce friction for clients to:

\* understand what you sell  
\* sign on  
\* engage with you  
\* get results  
\* brag on you (i.e. net promoter score is friction-reducing)

And you can do it internally. How much friction for team members to:  
\- know what to work on  
\- get answers to what they need  
\- access necessary resources  
\- give and receive feedback  
\- etc etc

Also interesting to note that reducing friction in some areas may temporarily increase friction in others:

\* customers easily giving feedback \-- creates friction in your priorities/product/etc  
\* blocking out time for high value work \-- creates friction for team members wanting immediate answers  
\* lowering friction on the sales side \-- could increase friction on the fulfillment side

You want to reduce friction for the things you want, then increase friction for the things you don't.
